<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-759-064  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 759 064.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Engineering  August 1990 v22 n8 p49(7).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hughes Aircraft designs automated storeroom system throughsimulation application. (Hughes Aircraft Company Radar SystemsGroup)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gogg, Thomas; Sands, Charles D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Hughes Aircraft Company Radar Systems Group is working to automateits storeroom operations.andP;  The new system combines six storeroomsin a single automated facility.andP;  Its basic elements are a poweredconveyor, robotic inserters and extractors, double stackedhorizontal carousels and tote pans.andP;  A bi-level powered beltconveyer is used to transport totes throughout the system.andP;  Totesare conveyed to workstations via the upper level and returned tocarousels via the lower level.andP;  The analysis of potential designconcepts became increasingly difficult as the number of elementsand relationships increased, thus making the system more complex.andO;Hughes chose WITNESS, a special purpose manufacturing simulator,to help design the automation system.andP;  Finding acceptable systemoperation under varying conditions became an essential part ofsystem planning and WITNESS helped speed the identification ofpossible flaws and defects.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hughes Aircraft Co. Radar Systems Group (automation).andO;Product:   WITNESS (Simulation software) (usage).andO;Topic:     AutomationFactory ManagementAnalysisSimulationModelingDesignCase StudyAerospace Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Top view of a system. (chart)Side view of a carousel stack. (chart)Conveyor speeds associated with various release cycle times.andO;(chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>